TY  - JOUR
T1  - Work-Unit Absenteeism: Effects of Satisfaction, Commitment, Labor Market Conditions, and Time
AU  - Hausknecht, John P.
AU  - Hiller, Nathan J.
AU  - Vance, Robert J.
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.35733022
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.35733022
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1223
EP  - 1245
VL  - 51
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Prior research is limited in explaining absenteeism at the unit level and over time. We developed and tested a model of unit-level absenteeism using five waves of data collected over six years from 115 work units in a large state agency. Unit-level job satisfaction, organizational commitment, and local unemployment were modeled as time-varying predictors of absenteeism. Shared satisfaction and commitment interacted in predicting absenteeism but were not related to the rate of change in absenteeism over time. Unit-level satisfaction and commitment were more strongly related to absenteeism when units were located in areas with plentiful job alternatives.
AB  - Prior research is limited in explaining absenteeism at the unit level and over time. We developed and tested a model of unit-level absenteeism using five waves of data collected over six years from 115 work units in a large state agency. Unit-level job satisfaction, organizational commitment, and local unemployment were modeled as time-varying predictors of absenteeism. Shared satisfaction and commitment interacted in predicting absenteeism but were not related to the rate of change in absenteeism over time. Unit-level satisfaction and commitment were more strongly related to absenteeism when units were located in areas with plentiful job alternatives.
