TY  - JOUR
T1  - Facing Differences With an Open Mind: Openness to Experience, Salience of Intragroup Differences, and Performance of Diverse Work Groups
AU  - Homan, Astrid C.
AU  - Hollenbeck, John R.
AU  - Humphrey, Stephen E.
AU  - Knippenberg, Daan Van
AU  - Ilgen, Daniel R.
AU  - Van Kleef, Gerben A.
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.35732995
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.35732995
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1204
EP  - 1222
VL  - 51
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examined how the performance of diverse teams is affected by member openness to experience and the extent to which team reward structure emphasizes intragroup differences. Fifty-eight heterogeneous four-person teams engaged in an interactive task. Teams in which reward structure converged with diversity (i.e., ?faultline? teams) performed more poorly than teams in which reward structure cut across differences between group members or pointed to a ?superordinate identity.? High openness to experience positively influenced teams in which differences were salient (i.e., faultline and ?cross-categorized? teams) but not teams with a superordi-nate identity. This effect was mediated by information elaboration.
AB  - This study examined how the performance of diverse teams is affected by member openness to experience and the extent to which team reward structure emphasizes intragroup differences. Fifty-eight heterogeneous four-person teams engaged in an interactive task. Teams in which reward structure converged with diversity (i.e., ?faultline? teams) performed more poorly than teams in which reward structure cut across differences between group members or pointed to a ?superordinate identity.? High openness to experience positively influenced teams in which differences were salient (i.e., faultline and ?cross-categorized? teams) but not teams with a superordi-nate identity. This effect was mediated by information elaboration.
