TY  - JOUR
T1  - Good Fences Make Good Neighbors: A Longitudinal Analysis of an Industry Self-Regulatory Institution
AU  - Barnett, Michael L.
AU  - King, Andrew A.
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.35732609
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.35732609
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1150
EP  - 1170
VL  - 51
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We extend theories of self-regulation of physical commons to analyze self-regulation of intangible commons in modern industry. We posit that when the action of one firm can cause ?spillover? harm to others, firms share a type of commons. We theorize that the need to protect this commons can motivate the formation of a self-regulatory institution. Using data from the U.S. chemical industry, we find that spillover harm from industrial accidents increased after a major industry crisis and decreased following the formation of a new institution. Additionally, our findings suggest that the institution lessened spillovers from participants to the broader industry.
AB  - We extend theories of self-regulation of physical commons to analyze self-regulation of intangible commons in modern industry. We posit that when the action of one firm can cause ?spillover? harm to others, firms share a type of commons. We theorize that the need to protect this commons can motivate the formation of a self-regulatory institution. Using data from the U.S. chemical industry, we find that spillover harm from industrial accidents increased after a major industry crisis and decreased following the formation of a new institution. Additionally, our findings suggest that the institution lessened spillovers from participants to the broader industry.
