TY  - JOUR
T1  - Entry into Emergent and Uncertain Product-Markets: The Role of Associative Rhetoric
AU  - Lee, Gwendolyn K.
AU  - Paruchuri, Srikanth
Y1  - 2008/12/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2008.35732614
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2008.35732614
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1171
EP  - 1188
VL  - 51
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We analyze how firms use media-associative rhetoric in their decisions to enter emergent and uncertain product-markets. In the context of our study, this type of rhetoric associates the logics of firms' existing markets with the not-yet-legitimated logics of a newly emerging market. Our panel study shows that firms enter such markets faster when the associative rhetoric has higher (versus lower) volume, positive (versus negative) tenor, firms (versus journalists/analysts) as the source of information, and generalizations (versus specific cases) as the focus. We discuss the implications of our findings for institutional theory and market entry.
AB  - We analyze how firms use media-associative rhetoric in their decisions to enter emergent and uncertain product-markets. In the context of our study, this type of rhetoric associates the logics of firms' existing markets with the not-yet-legitimated logics of a newly emerging market. Our panel study shows that firms enter such markets faster when the associative rhetoric has higher (versus lower) volume, positive (versus negative) tenor, firms (versus journalists/analysts) as the source of information, and generalizations (versus specific cases) as the focus. We discuss the implications of our findings for institutional theory and market entry.
